{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "GEOSChemRateLaws",
        "description": "GEOS-Chem gas-phase reaction rate laws \u2014 the 37 rate-coefficient builder functions of GasChem.jl src/geoschem_ratelaws.jl, adapted from the GEOS-Chem KPP/fullchem mechanism (github.com/geoschem/geos-chem, commit 4722f288). Each builder computes a single reaction rate coefficient k from temperature and air number density: constant rates (constant_k, constant_k_1), modified-Arrhenius forms in ppb and SI molecular units (arrhenius_ppb, arrhenius_ppb_3, arrhenius_mlc_SI, arrhenius_mlc_1, arrplus_*, tunplus_*), Troe / third-body pressure-dependent falloff rates (arr_3rdbody, arr_3rdbody_1, rate_OHCO, rate_PAN_abab, rate_PAN_acac, eq_const, eq_const_1), and a family of mechanism-specific rates for HO2, RO2+NO, isoprene, glycolaldehyde, DMS and HNO3 chemistry. Each rate law is migrated as an independent purely-algebraic model: the inputs (T, num_density, Arrhenius coefficients) are parameters, the rate coefficient k is the single state variable defined by one algebraic equation, and an inline test reproduces the rate constant asserted by the corresponding @testitem in GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl (compiled at T=293 K, num_density = 2.7e19 molec/cm^3). The GEOS-Chem license applies (github.com/geoschem/geos-chem/blob/main/LICENSE.txt).",
        "tags": [
            "gaschem",
            "geoschem",
            "rate-laws",
            "reaction-kinetics",
            "arrhenius",
            "troposphere-chemistry",
            "observed-only"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "GasChem.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-wb5s)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "GEOS-Chem KPP/fullchem rate laws, adapted in GasChem.jl src/geoschem_ratelaws.jl. Upstream mechanism: the GEOS-Chem chemical mechanism, github.com/geoschem/geos-chem/tree/4722f288e90291ba904222f4bbe4fc216d17c34a/KPP/fullchem. JPL/IUPAC kinetic recommendations underlie the individual Arrhenius and Troe-falloff forms.",
                "url": "https://github.com/geoschem/geos-chem"
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "constant_k": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/geoschem_ratelaws.jl:11 (`constant_k` rate-law builder function).\n\nConstant rate coefficient for a second-order reaction. The supplied coefficient c (cm^3 molec^-1 s^-1) is converted to ppb^-1 s^-1 via the air number density: k = c * (N_A/cm3_m3) * num_density * ppb_unit.\n\nMigration shape: the upstream `constant_k` returns a Catalyst `ReactionSystem` carrying zero reactions and one variable k(t) bound by a single algebraic equation k ~ <rate expression> (the @constants in the source are MTK unit-bookkeeping; their numeric values N_A=6.02214076e23, cm3_m3=1.0e6, ppb_unit=1.0e-9, k_unit_inv=1.0e6 are folded into the .esm expression AST as literals). It is migrated here as a purely-algebraic `model`: the rate-law inputs (T, num_density, Arrhenius coefficients) are `type: parameter`, the output k is the single `type: state` variable, and `equations` holds the one defining equation. No equation carries a D(.) operator, so the trajectory is constant in time and the inline test samples at t=0 (the observed-only convention of sibling files multiple_removal.esm / ope.esm).\n\nUnits: variables carry no `units` field \u2014 the rate expression folds the upstream MTK unit conversions into numeric literals, so every quantity is nominally dimensionless to the structural validator. This is the convention of the sibling GEOS-Chem file geoschem_fullchem.esm; physical units are documented in prose in each variable's `description`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8 / abs=1e-30): the rate law is a single closed-form algebraic expression evaluated once (no time integration, no stiff dynamics). rel=1e-8 sits at the upstream Julia approximate-equality default (`approx` uses rtol=sqrt(eps(Float64))=~1.49e-8) and comfortably absorbs the libm exp / ^ / log10 rounding differences between the Julia reference values and the Python ESS runner; abs=1e-30 is a near-zero floor that gates no assertion here (the smallest pinned rate constant across the file is eq_const k=~2.1e-27).\n\nUpstream test reproduction: the inline test `upstream_constant_k` pins k at the parameter defaults to the value asserted by the `@testitem \"constant_k\"` block in GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl, which compiles the rate law at T=293.0 K and num_density=2.7e19/N_A*cm3_m3 mol/m^3 and checks the resulting rate constant k."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08,
                "abs": 1e-30
            },
            "variables": {
                "num_density": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 44.834554813693856,
                    "description": "Number density of air (mol/m^3). Default 44.834554813693856 mol/m^3 equals 2.7e19 molec/cm^3 \u2014 the upstream test value 2.7e19/N_A*cm3_m3 (N_A = 6.02214076e23, cm3_m3 = 1.0e6)."
                },
                "c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 1.8e-12,
                    "description": "Second-order rate coefficient in molecular units. [cm^3*molec^-1*s^-1]"
                },
                "k": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "description": "Reaction rate coefficient produced by the constant_k rate law, output in ppb^-1*s^-1. Defined by one algebraic equation; the system carries no time derivative."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "k",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "c",
                            6.02214076e+17,
                            "num_density",
                            1e-09
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_constant_k",
                    "description": "Reproduces the upstream `constant_k` rate-law test (GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl). All parameters are at their declared defaults \u2014 the exact coefficient values the upstream @testitem passes to `constant_k` \u2014 and the rate coefficient k is pinned to the upstream expected value 0.0486.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
                        {
                            "variable": "k",
                            "time": 0.0,
                            "expected": 0.0486
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        "constant_k_1": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/geoschem_ratelaws.jl:27 (`constant_k_1` rate-law builder function).\n\nConstant rate coefficient for a first-order reaction: k = c, the supplied first-order coefficient passed through unchanged (s^-1).\n\nMigration shape: the upstream `constant_k_1` returns a Catalyst `ReactionSystem` carrying zero reactions and one variable k(t) bound by a single algebraic equation k ~ <rate expression> (the @constants in the source are MTK unit-bookkeeping; their numeric values N_A=6.02214076e23, cm3_m3=1.0e6, ppb_unit=1.0e-9, k_unit_inv=1.0e6 are folded into the .esm expression AST as literals). It is migrated here as a purely-algebraic `model`: the rate-law inputs (T, num_density, Arrhenius coefficients) are `type: parameter`, the output k is the single `type: state` variable, and `equations` holds the one defining equation. No equation carries a D(.) operator, so the trajectory is constant in time and the inline test samples at t=0 (the observed-only convention of sibling files multiple_removal.esm / ope.esm).\n\nUnits: variables carry no `units` field \u2014 the rate expression folds the upstream MTK unit conversions into numeric literals, so every quantity is nominally dimensionless to the structural validator. This is the convention of the sibling GEOS-Chem file geoschem_fullchem.esm; physical units are documented in prose in each variable's `description`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8 / abs=1e-30): the rate law is a single closed-form algebraic expression evaluated once (no time integration, no stiff dynamics). rel=1e-8 sits at the upstream Julia approximate-equality default (`approx` uses rtol=sqrt(eps(Float64))=~1.49e-8) and comfortably absorbs the libm exp / ^ / log10 rounding differences between the Julia reference values and the Python ESS runner; abs=1e-30 is a near-zero floor that gates no assertion here (the smallest pinned rate constant across the file is eq_const k=~2.1e-27).\n\nUpstream test reproduction: the inline test `upstream_constant_k_1` pins k at the parameter defaults to the value asserted by the `@testitem \"constant_k_1\"` block in GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl, which compiles the rate law at T=293.0 K and num_density=2.7e19/N_A*cm3_m3 mol/m^3 and checks the resulting rate constant k."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08,
                "abs": 1e-30
            },
            "variables": {
                "c": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 1.8e-12,
                    "description": "First-order rate coefficient. [s^-1]"
                },
                "k": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "description": "Reaction rate coefficient produced by the constant_k_1 rate law, output in s^-1. Defined by one algebraic equation; the system carries no time derivative."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "k",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "c",
                            1.0
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "upstream_constant_k_1",
                    "description": "Reproduces the upstream `constant_k_1` rate-law test (GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl). All parameters are at their declared defaults \u2014 the exact coefficient values the upstream @testitem passes to `constant_k_1` \u2014 and the rate coefficient k is pinned to the upstream expected value 1.8e-12.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {},
                    "time_span": {
                        "start": 0.0,
                        "end": 1.0
                    },
                    "assertions": [
