        "arrhenius_ppb_3": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: GasChem.jl@8c12c048482b515fb8eb2110bf8ab4b4f4e71309:src/geoschem_ratelaws.jl:89 (`arrhenius_ppb_3` rate-law builder function).\n\nModified Arrhenius rate law for a third-order reaction, output in ppb^-2 s^-1: k = a0*exp(c0/T)*(300/T)^b0 * C, with C = num_density^2 * ppb_unit^2 * (N_A/cm3_m3)^2.\n\nMigration shape: the upstream `arrhenius_ppb_3` returns a Catalyst `ReactionSystem` carrying zero reactions and one variable k(t) bound by a single algebraic equation k ~ <rate expression> (the @constants in the source are MTK unit-bookkeeping; their numeric values N_A=6.02214076e23, cm3_m3=1.0e6, ppb_unit=1.0e-9, k_unit_inv=1.0e6 are folded into the .esm expression AST as literals). It is migrated here as a purely-algebraic `model`: the rate-law inputs (T, num_density, Arrhenius coefficients) are `type: parameter`, the output k is the single `type: state` variable, and `equations` holds the one defining equation. No equation carries a D(.) operator, so the trajectory is constant in time and the inline test samples at t=0 (the observed-only convention of sibling files multiple_removal.esm / ope.esm).\n\nUnits: variables carry no `units` field \u2014 the rate expression folds the upstream MTK unit conversions into numeric literals, so every quantity is nominally dimensionless to the structural validator. This is the convention of the sibling GEOS-Chem file geoschem_fullchem.esm; physical units are documented in prose in each variable's `description`.\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-8 / abs=1e-30): the rate law is a single closed-form algebraic expression evaluated once (no time integration, no stiff dynamics). rel=1e-8 sits at the upstream Julia approximate-equality default (`approx` uses rtol=sqrt(eps(Float64))=~1.49e-8) and comfortably absorbs the libm exp / ^ / log10 rounding differences between the Julia reference values and the Python ESS runner; abs=1e-30 is a near-zero floor that gates no assertion here (the smallest pinned rate constant across the file is eq_const k=~2.1e-27).\n\nUpstream test reproduction: the inline test `upstream_arrhenius_ppb_3` pins k at the parameter defaults to the value asserted by the `@testitem \"arrhenius_ppb_3\"` block in GasChem.jl test/geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl, which compiles the rate law at T=293.0 K and num_density=2.7e19/N_A*cm3_m3 mol/m^3 and checks the resulting rate constant k."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-08,
                "abs": 1e-30
            },
            "variables": {
                "T": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 293.0,
                    "description": "Air temperature (K). Default 293.0 K is the scenario temperature of the upstream geoschem_ratelaws_test.jl `RateLawSetup` test snippet."
                },
                "num_density": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 44.834554813693856,
                    "description": "Number density of air (mol/m^3). Default 44.834554813693856 mol/m^3 equals 2.7e19 molec/cm^3 \u2014 the upstream test value 2.7e19/N_A*cm3_m3 (N_A = 6.02214076e23, cm3_m3 = 1.0e6)."
                },
                "a0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 2.9e-16,
                    "description": "Pre-exponential factor."
                },
                "b0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": 0.0,
                    "description": "Temperature-power exponent."
                },
                "c0": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "default": -1000.0,
                    "description": "Arrhenius exponential temperature term. [K]"
                },
                "k": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "description": "Reaction rate coefficient produced by the arrhenius_ppb_3 rate law, output in ppb^-2*s^-1. Defined by one algebraic equation; the system carries no time derivative."
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "k",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "*",
                        "args": [
                            "a0",
                            {
                                "op": "exp",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            "c0",
                                            "T"
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "^",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "/",
                                        "args": [
                                            300.0,
                                            "T"
                                        ]
                                    },
                                    "b0"
                                ]
                            },
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    {
                                        "op": "^",
                                        "args": [
                                            "num_density",
                                            2.0
                                        ]
